If your blood glucose level is higher than normal but not high enough to be
diagnosed as type 2 diabetes, you may have a condition called pre-diabetes.
This means your body’s insulin is not working effectively.
Pre-diabetes is also known as impaired glucose tolerance, impaired fasting
glucose or insulin resistance. It's estimated that two million Australians are
## What are the risks associated with pre-diabetes?
Pre-diabetes can increase your risk of cardiovascular (heart and blood vessel)
disease, which can lead to heart attack and stroke.
Left untreated, pre-diabetes can develop into type 2 diabetes within five to
10 years. However, leading a healthy lifestyle can help you manage pre-
diabetes and reduce your risk of developing type 2 diabetes – so the earlier
Pre-diabetes is diagnosed with an oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT). Your
doctor can order this simple test and you can have it at a pathology
laboratory. If you think you may be at risk of pre-diabetes, talk to your
Find out about pre-diabetes and understand your risk
